 y2dc ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">out of the sea, denoting an organization among the nations. </div><div class="t m1f3 x28 he y48b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">2. </div><div class="t mb33 x5b he y48b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The seven heads and the ten horns connect this beast </div><div class="t m1718 x4a he y2b9 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">with the dragon. That the beast is religious is shown by </div><div class="t m435 x4a he y8e3 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the names of blasphemy. One of the definitions of blasphemy </div><div class="t mbdc x4a he y626 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">is, claiming the attributes of God. </div><div class="t m104a x28 he y90 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3. </div><div class="t m12fb x5b he y90 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The &quot;leopard,&quot; Grecia; the &quot;bear,&quot; Medo-Persia; the </div><div class="t m530 x4a he y9ab ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;lion,&quot; Babylon; the &quot;ten horns,&quot; Rome ..(Dan. 7: 3-7), show </div><div class="t mad0 x14 he y5d ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">this beast of our lesson to be the composite of all four of </div><div class="t m1571 x14 he y37b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Daniel. Daniel sees them as four distinct, successive em-</div><div class="t m1bbd x14 he ye1 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">pires. John sees them as one great system, culminating in </div><div class="t m41a x14 he y1c14 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Rome papal, represented in Daniel&apos;s vision by the little horn </div><div class="t m1017 x4a he y16 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">of chapter 7. Note the parallels between the first beast of </div><div class="t m6b1 x14 he y65 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Revelation 13 and the little horn power. (Compare Rev. </div><div class="t m1a2f x4a he y94a ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">13: 2, 5, 6, 7, 10 and Dan. 7: 8, 20, 21, 25, 26.) It must not </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
